{"result": "## (MXene<|>PVSCs<|>MATERIAL PROPERTY<|>TRUE<|>NONE<|>NONE<|>MXene materials with different surface functional groups can be used as electron transport layers (ETLs) in perovskite solar cells (PVSCs). The work function (WF) of MXene is an important property that affects the performance of PVSCs. The WF of MXene should be adjusted close to the conduction band minimum (CBM) of the perovskite layer to ensure effective electron transportation. The amino-functionalized MXene with abundant NH2 groups exhibits a lower WF of 4.32 eV compared with the pristine MXene (P·Nb2CTx) after replacing the surface terminated -F groups with -NH2 groups. This lower WF is beneficial for the electron transport in PVSCs.<|>The WF of the pristine Nb2CTx MXene ETL with -OH, -O, and -F groups (4.7 eV) is much lower than the conduction band minimum (CBM) of the perovskite layer (3.9 eV), which leads to severe energy loss at the Nb2CTx MXene ETL/perovskite interface and limits the performance of the PVSCs. Therefore, the WF of Nb2CTx MXene should be adjusted close to the CBM of perovskite layer to ensure effective electron transportation before serving as the ETL of PVSCs. Huang et al. regulated the WF of Nb2CTx MXene by controlling the ratio of the surface functional groups (-F, -OH, and -O) and used them as charge transport layers to fabricate organic solar cells with PCE over 15%. Previously, we successfully prepared Nb2CTx MXene nanosheets and enhanced their WF by increasing the surface -O groups through oxygen plasma treatment. The treated Nb2CTx MXene with abundant -O groups exhibited high WF of 5.04 eV and excellent hole transport ability. The p-i-n structure PVSCs using the treated Nb2CTx MXene achieved the highest PCE of 20.74% and exhibited good stability. However, the properties of MXene containing other surface functional groups and their applications in the PVSC devices are rarely studied. Therefore, it is of great significance to further research the properties of MXene materials with other surface functional groups (-NH2, -COOH, -SO3H, et al.) and expand their application in PVSCs, because these surface functional groups can interact with perovskite ions and affect the device performance.<|>In this work, Nb2CTx MXene with -NH2 surface functional groups is prepared by hydrazine treatment and its optoelectrical properties are deeply investigated. Different from the -O functionalization Nb2CTx MXene (with high WF of 5.04 eV) we prepared previously, the amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene prepared in this work possesses a lower WF of 4.32 eV compared with the pristine Nb2CTx MXene (P·Nb2CTx) after replacing the surface terminated -F groups with -NH2 groups. Besides, the amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene with abundant ·NH2 groups is incorporated into the perovskite precursor to retard the crystallization rate by forming hydrogen bond with I- in the perovskite precursor. Consequently, the PVSCs with amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene as ETL and additive achieve the highest PCE of 21.79% with excellent stability. The optimized flexible and large-area devices also show considerable PCE of 19.15% and 18.31%.)\n##\n(Nb2CTx MXene<|>PVSCs<|>SYNTHESIS ROLE<|>TRUE<|>NONE<|>NONE<|>Nb2CTx MXene is used as an electron transport layer (ETL) in perovskite solar cells (PVSCs). The amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene with abundant NH2 groups is prepared by hydrazine treatment and incorporated into the perovskite precursor to retard the crystallization rate by forming hydrogen bonds with I- in the perovskite precursor. This incorporation of amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene as ETL and additive leads to the highest power conversion efficiency (PCE) of 21.79% with excellent stability in PVSCs.<|>In this work, Nb2CTx MXene with -NH2 surface functional groups is prepared by hydrazine treatment and its optoelectrical properties are deeply investigated. Different from the -O functionalization Nb2CTx MXene (with high WF of 5.04 eV) we prepared previously, the amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene prepared in this work possesses a lower WF of 4.32 eV compared with the pristine Nb2CTx MXene (P·Nb2CTx) after replacing the surface terminated -F groups with -NH2 groups. Besides, the amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene with abundant ·NH2 groups is incorporated into the perovskite precursor to retard the crystallization rate by forming hydrogen bond with I- in the perovskite precursor. Consequently, the PVSCs with amino-functionalized Nb2CTx MXene as ETL and additive achieve the highest PCE of 21.79% with excellent stability. The optimized flexible and large-area devices also show considerable PCE of 19.15% and 18.31%.)\n##\n(Nb2CTx MXene<|>organic solar cells<|>SYNTHESIS ROLE<|>TRUE<|>NONE<|>NONE<|>Nb2CTx MXene is used as a charge transport layer in organic solar cells. Huang et al. regulated the work function (WF) of Nb2CTx MXene by controlling the ratio of the surface functional groups (-F, -OH, and -O) and used them as charge transport layers to fabricate organic solar cells with power conversion efficiency (PCE) over 15%.<|>Huang et al. regulated the WF of Nb2CTx MXene by controlling the ratio of the surface functional groups (-F, -OH, and -O) and used them as charge transport layers to fabricate organic solar cells with PCE over 15%.)\n##\n(Nb2CTx MXene<|>TEM<|>CHARACTERIZATION METHOD<|>TRUE<|>NONE<|>NONE<|>Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) is used to characterize the morphology and structure of Nb2CTx MXene. The TEM images of the P·Nb2CTx and the Nb2CTx treated with N2H4 for 12h (T·Nb2CTx) MXenes are shown in Figure 1b,d. The TEM images of the Nb2CTx MXene treated with N2H4 for 3, 7, and 18h are shown in Figure S1a–c, Supporting Information. All Nb2CTx MXenes exhibit a typical 2D morphology with a size of about 200 nm and the electron-transparent feature indicates an ultrathin characteristic of the nanosheets.<|>The transmission electron microscope (TEM) images of the P·Nb2CTx and the Nb2CTx treated with N2H4 for 12h (T·Nb2